"Trick C.G., Bill B.D., Cochlan W.P., Wells M.L., Trainer V.L., Pickell L.D.","Iron enrichment stimulates toxic diatom production in high-nitrate, low-chlorophyll areas",2010,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","107","13",,"5887","5892",,,10.1073/pnas.0910579107,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77950534702&partnerID=40&md5=661de978abc44d91f8a8fc4e2c7dac5a","Departments of Biology, and Microbiology and Immunology, Schulich School of Medicine and Dentistry, University of Western Ontario, London, ON N6A5B7, Canada; Romberg Tiburon Center for Environmental Studies, San Francisco State University, Tiburon, CA 94920, United States; Marine Biotoxin Program, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Northwest Fisheries Science Center, Seattle, WA 98112, United States; School of Marine Science, University of Maine, Orono, ME 04469, United States","Trick, C.G., Departments of Biology, and Microbiology and Immunology, Schulich School of Medicine and Dentistry, University of Western Ontario, London, ON N6A5B7, Canada; Bill, B.D., Romberg Tiburon Center for Environmental Studies, San Francisco State University, Tiburon, CA 94920, United States, Marine Biotoxin Program, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Northwest Fisheries Science Center, Seattle, WA 98112, United States; Cochlan, W.P., Romberg Tiburon Center for Environmental Studies, San Francisco State University, Tiburon, CA 94920, United States; Wells, M.L., School of Marine Science, University of Maine, Orono, ME 04469, United States; Trainer, V.L., Marine Biotoxin Program, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Northwest Fisheries Science Center, Seattle, WA 98112, United States; Pickell, L.D., School of Marine Science, University of Maine, Orono, ME 04469, United States","Oceanic high-nitrate, low-chlorophyll environments have been high-lighted for potential large-scale iron fertilizations to help mitigate global climate change. Controversy surrounds these initiatives, both in the degree of carbon removal and magnitude of ecosystem impacts. Previous open ocean enrichment experiments have shown that iron additions stimulate growth of the toxigenic diatom genus Pseudonitzschia. Most Pseudonitzschia species in coastal waters produce the neurotoxin domoic acid (DA), with their blooms causing detrimental marine ecosystem impacts, but oceanic Pseudonitzschia species areconsiderednontoxic.Herewedemonstrate that thesparse oceanic Pseudonitzschia community at the high-nitrate, low-chlorophyll Ocean Station PAPA (50° N, 145° W) produces approximately 200 pg DA L-1 in response to iron addition, that DA alters phytoplankton community structure to benefit Pseudonitzschia, and that oceanic cell isolates are toxic. Given the negative effects of DA in coastal food webs, these findings raise serious concern over the net benefit and sustainability of large-scale iron fertilizations.","Carbon sequestering; Domoic acid; Ocean iron fertilization; Pseudonitzschia; Toxicity","chlorophyll; domoic acid; iron; nitrate; article; cell isolation; community structure; controlled study; fertilization; food web; marine environment; microbial community; nonhuman; phytoplankton; priority journal; Pseudonitzschia; species; Chlorophyll; Climate Change; Copper; Diatoms; Ecosystem; Iron; Kainic Acid; Marine Toxins; Neurotoxins; Nitrates; Seawater; Bacillariophyta; Pseudo-nitzschia",,"chlorophyll, 1406-65-1, 15611-43-5; domoic acid, 14277-97-5; iron, 14093-02-8, 53858-86-9, 7439-89-6; nitrate, 14797-55-8; Chlorophyll, 1406-65-1; Copper, 7440-50-8; Iron, 7439-89-6; Kainic Acid, 487-79-6; Marine Toxins; Neurotoxins; Nitrates; domoic acid, 14277-97-5",,,,"Buesseler, K.O., Environment. Ocean iron fertilization - Moving forward in a sea of uncertainty (2008) Science, 319, p. 162; Boyd, P.W., Mesoscale iron enrichment experiments 1993-2005: Synthesis and future directions (2007) Science, 315, pp. 612-617; De Baar, H.J.W., Synthesis of iron fertilization experiments: From the iron age in the age of enlightenment (2005) J Geophys Res, 110, pp. C09S16; Buesseler, K.O., Boyd, P.W., Climate change. Will ocean fertilization work? (2003) Science, 300, pp. 67-68; Chisholm, S.W., Falkowski, P.G., Cullen, J.J., Oceans. Dis-crediting ocean fertilization (2001) Science, 294, pp. 309-310; Coale, K.H., A massive phytoplankton bloom induced by an ecosystem-scale iron fertilization experiment in the equatorial Pacific Ocean (1996) Nature, 383, pp. 495-501. , 501; Landry, M.R., Biological response to iron fertilization in the eastern equatorial Pacific (IronEx II). I. Microplankton community abundances and biomass (2000) Mar Ecol Prog Ser, 201, pp. 27-42; Boyd, P.W., A mesoscale phytoplankton bloom in the polar Southern Ocean stimulated by iron fertilization (2000) Nature, 407, pp. 695-702; Gervais, F., Riebesell, U., Gorbunov, M.Y., Changes in primary productivity and chlorophyll a in response to iron fertilization in the Southern Polar Frontal Zone (2002) Limnol Oceanogr, 47, pp. 1324-1335; Coale, K.H., Southern Ocean iron enrichment experiment: Carbon cycling in high- and low-Si waters (2004) Science, 304, pp. 408-414; Peloquin, J.A., Smith Jr., W.O., The role of phytoplankton size on photochemical recovery during the Southern Ocean iron experiment (2006) Journal of Phycology, 42 (5), pp. 1016-1027. , DOI 10.1111/j.1529-8817.2006.00266.x; Trainer, V.L., Domoic acid production near California coastal upwelling zones (2000) Limnol Oceanogr, 45, pp. 1818-1833. , June 1998; Trainer, V.L., An ecological study of a massive toxigenic bloom of Pseudonitzschia cuspidata off the Washington State coast (2009) Limnol Oceanogr, 54, pp. 1461-1474; Scholin, C.A., Mortality of sea lions along the central California coast linked to a toxic diatom bloom (2000) Nature, 403, pp. 80-84; Assmy, P., Henjes, J., Klaas, C., Smetacek, V., Mechanisms determining species dominance in a phytoplankton bloom induced by the iron fertiliz